desc: Tract Diag Effect v1 (uniform tube — audio in, shaped through tract)
// Designed by Rozaya, developed with Claude (Anthropic)
//
// This work is dedicated to the public domain under CC0 1.0 Universal.
// https://creativecommons.org/publicdomain/zero/1.0/
//
// Effect-form companion to tract_diag_v1. Same uniform-tube waveguide
// — same scatter code, same boundary equations, same constants —
// but instead of generating its own excitation, this plugin TAKES
// audio input and feeds it into the tract at the glottal end. Stereo
// input is mixed to mono first (real vocal tracts are mono).
//
// Intended workflow:
//   Track FX chain:  [Breath Generator] -> [Tract Diag Effect]
//
// Breath Generator produces shaped breath noise (inhale/exhale
// envelope, post-filter, stereo width, etc.); this plugin takes
// that signal and pushes it through the Kelly-Lochbaum waveguide.
// What comes out the lip end should sound like that breath
// spectrally COLORED by tube resonances — formant-flavored breath.
//
// This is the right question to ask: not "can we make breath from
// scratch" (Breath Generator already does), but "does the waveguide
// audibly shape breath when fed into it." If yes, the path to
// vowel-articulated breath ("hih.hooo") is unlocked — we just need
// to add tongue/lip diameter controls back ONE AT A TIME, with ear
// validation each step, on this same proven foundation.

slider1:0.0<-24.0,24.0,0.1>Input Gain (dB) — how hot the breath drives the tract
slider2:0.9998<0.99,0.99999,0.00001>Damping per scatter step
slider3:1.5<0.1,3.0,0.05>Tube diameter (uniform; should NOT change formant pitch)
slider4:0<0,1,1{No,Yes}>DC blocker on output
slider5:0.5<0.0,1.0,0.01>Output Volume

@init
N = 44;
R = 0; L = 64; JR = 128; JL = 192; refl_bank = 256;

glottalReflection = 0.75;
lipReflection     = -0.85;

i = 0; loop(N, R[i] = 0; L[i] = 0; JR[i] = 0; JL[i] = 0; refl_bank[i] = 0; i += 1; );

damp     = 0.9998;
in_gain  = 1.0;
dc_x     = 0;
dc_y     = 0;

// scatter() is BIT-IDENTICAL to tract_tube_v5 and tract_diag_v1.
// We're not testing scatter — we're testing whether the proven-good
// scatter audibly shapes an external audio input.
function scatter(gin) local(j, k, w) (
  JR[0]   = gin + glottalReflection * L[0];
  JL[N-1] = lipReflection * R[N-1];
  j = 1;
  while (j < N) (
    k = refl_bank[j];
    w = k * (R[j-1] + L[j]);
    JR[j]   = R[j-1] - w;
    JL[j-1] = L[j]   + w;
    j += 1;
  );
  j = 0;
  while (j < N) (
    R[j] = JR[j] * damp;
    L[j] = JL[j] * damp;
    j += 1;
  );
);

@slider
// dB -> linear gain.
in_gain   = 10 ^ (slider1 / 20);
damp      = slider2;
tube_dia  = slider3;
dc_on     = slider4;
vol       = slider5;

// Uniform tube — every segment same diameter, every internal
// reflection coefficient = 0. Wave propagates freely; only glottal
// and lip boundaries reflect.
i = 1;
while (i < N) ( refl_bank[i] = 0; i += 1; );

@sample
// === Take audio input as the excitation source ===
// Mix stereo to mono (real tracts are mono physically). The breath
// you're feeding in already has its envelope, fades, stereo shaping,
// etc. baked in from Breath Generator — we just want one signal to
// push through the tube.
in_mono = (spl0 + spl1) * 0.5 * in_gain;

// === 2x-rate scattering (identical structure to tract_tube_v5) ===
// Both scatter calls receive the SAME input sample. This matches v5
// and Pink Trombone's convention: the tract runs at 2x the audio
// rate; the source is sampled at audio rate.
scatter(in_mono); o1 = R[N-1];
scatter(in_mono); o2 = R[N-1];
lipout = (o1 + o2) * 0.5;

// === Optional DC blocker ===
// Noise input can accumulate DC bias in the waveguide. The blocker
// is a first-order high-pass at very low frequency (~7 Hz at 44.1
// kHz). Toggleable so you can A/B with and without it.
dc_on > 0 ? (
  dc_y = lipout - dc_x + 0.997 * dc_y;
  dc_x = lipout;
  out  = dc_y;
) : (
  out  = lipout;
);

spl0 = out * vol;
spl1 = out * vol;
